1
00:00:04,434 --> 00:00:16,568
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambhodassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:18,370 --> 00:00:23,858
So if you can imagine what it was like for the Buddha to leave his family.

3
00:00:24,178 --> 00:00:28,704
So he's 29, he's married and he's just had a child born.

4
00:00:29,384 --> 00:00:32,468
So it's not as though he made a sudden decision, he's off.

5
00:00:33,037 --> 00:00:35,542
It must have been hanging around for quite some time.

6
00:00:35,582 --> 00:00:53,591
And I often wonder whether his marriage was in good faith, bad faith, according to the philosopher Sartre, you know, just to follow customs and not to follow what your heart's really telling you.

7
00:00:54,652 --> 00:00:57,898
And I'm wondering whether the birth of his child was like a

8
00:00:58,570 --> 00:01:02,914
a crisis point where he realized he wasn't ready to be a father or whatever.

9
00:01:04,316 --> 00:01:14,868
But obviously, during that late youth, round about 25 onwards, there is usually a sort of an awakening to the fact that youth is passing.

10
00:01:15,750 --> 00:01:21,496
And for some people, it can be like a midlife, an early midlife crisis.

11
00:01:23,138 --> 00:01:25,421
So he leaves anyway.

12
00:01:26,076 --> 00:01:36,849
I can't imagine he was happy about leaving, but determined to do so, perhaps just to taste the life of the Samana, the recluse, the wandering recluse.

13
00:01:38,091 --> 00:01:45,120
And then what drives him is, of course, this urge to try and get beyond suffering.

14
00:01:45,200 --> 00:01:47,442
So that was the big theme of the age.

15
00:01:48,165 --> 00:01:51,370
Everybody was concerned about bringing suffering to an end.

16
00:01:51,471 --> 00:01:58,180
Some thought, well, if you practice the jhana, these absorptions, that's where you ended up forever in these heavens.

17
00:01:58,980 --> 00:02:01,805
Others were materialists, but were materialists.

18
00:02:01,825 --> 00:02:03,808
You know, they just said, well, when you die, you die.

19
00:02:07,313 --> 00:02:13,801
So he goes in search of teachers and he's probably already known, he knows them already because one of the

20
00:02:14,473 --> 00:02:29,987
entertainments of the age was to go out into the park at full moon, and the full moon in the east is really almost like the sun coming out, and to listen to these debates where these religious leaders would try to better each other.

21
00:02:32,750 --> 00:02:43,620
So he was well into it, and we know that because after he becomes liberated, he's able to hold his own with his arguments and understandings.

22
00:02:43,972 --> 00:02:50,557
So he's well into the whole spiritual, religious turmoil that was part of that time.

23
00:02:51,079 --> 00:03:00,207
And it was the same time that the Jain leader was there and all the Upanishads, you know, the Hindu scriptures began to appear.

24
00:03:00,848 --> 00:03:04,110
So it's an age of sort of an awakening.

25
00:03:05,132 --> 00:03:07,594
I was going to say a bit like ours, but I'm not sure about that.

26
00:03:10,257 --> 00:03:10,957
And

27
00:03:12,118 --> 00:03:19,306
He tries, of course, these various teachers and the first two tell him how to get into these blissful states.

28
00:03:20,287 --> 00:03:24,512
And in both cases, he's good enough to become a teacher in that tradition.

29
00:03:25,513 --> 00:03:34,502
And in both cases, he leaves because when he comes out of those states, you know, he's back to being anxious, depressed, etc.

30
00:03:35,163 --> 00:03:39,526
So they've not answered his some fundamental urge within him.

31
00:03:39,929 --> 00:03:47,856
to find if there's an end to suffering, which I think for him would have been the end of rebirth, because it's there in the scriptures.

32
00:03:49,237 --> 00:03:52,360
He often talks about, and this is the end of becoming, right?

33
00:03:53,162 --> 00:03:57,346
Now, you have to underline that as the end of becoming as a self, right?

34
00:03:59,548 --> 00:04:08,956
So then he tries this other form, this very hard ascetic practice with the understanding, which I think was a Jain understanding,

35
00:04:09,562 --> 00:04:21,540
there's some hint that he was following that practice, that the soul, the eternal soul was trapped in the body and that the body was a manifestation of your bad karma.

36
00:04:22,600 --> 00:04:26,346
So if you didn't have eyes, you wouldn't have lust.

37
00:04:26,666 --> 00:04:29,451
If you didn't have a tongue, you wouldn't have greed.

38
00:04:29,471 --> 00:04:31,675
So the idea was to draw the body down.

39
00:04:32,956 --> 00:04:35,259
And that was done mainly through fasting.

40
00:04:35,300 --> 00:04:38,504
And he got so thin, he said, he could hold his spine through his stomach.

41
00:04:38,889 --> 00:04:41,031
So if you try that, you'll see he was very thin.

42
00:04:42,052 --> 00:04:48,259
And at some point, if you can imagine it, he's there with six companions who probably have been with him all that time.

43
00:04:48,338 --> 00:04:56,466
So they're close mates, spiritual companions, you know, all urging each other to be more and more ascetic.

44
00:04:57,708 --> 00:05:01,430
And at some point, he realizes he's not getting anywhere.

45
00:05:01,752 --> 00:05:03,112
He's just more suffering, he says.

46
00:05:03,853 --> 00:05:04,514
And he leaves.

47
00:05:06,935 --> 00:05:07,497
I mean...

48
00:05:07,915 --> 00:05:34,091
i'm sure that in all our lives you know we've taken up something and then realize it's not working for us and we're going to start again we've got to go somewhere else got to find another way of spending life you know so i can only imagine that he's pretty depressed in our terms and uh we have the one biographical

49
00:05:34,358 --> 00:05:36,841
Well, no, it's not the only one.

50
00:05:37,101 --> 00:05:37,622
There's two.

51
00:05:37,663 --> 00:05:45,413
There's two fairly acceptable biographical points in his life that we know about.

52
00:05:45,574 --> 00:05:59,935
There's something in his early life, which I'll come to, and there's this point where he's sitting on a road and a woman with offerings for the local god offers him some, you know, a mince pie.

53
00:06:01,117 --> 00:06:01,377
And

54
00:06:01,983 --> 00:06:06,267
it revives him and it makes him sort of consider what he's doing.

55
00:06:08,389 --> 00:06:12,714
And that's when some sort of determination takes him to have one more go.

56
00:06:14,677 --> 00:06:27,932
And it comes from this memory, which is understood to be a real, true biographical moment where he remembers watching his father doing a ploughing ceremony.

57
00:06:29,473 --> 00:06:30,555
And

58
00:06:31,261 --> 00:06:38,668
He remembers himself being concentrated and full of inquiry, full of a sense of curiosity.

59
00:06:40,230 --> 00:06:46,255
And I think that means that his whole approach completely turned around on itself.

60
00:06:46,877 --> 00:06:54,024
Instead of trying to get rid of suffering, he now turns towards it to find out what the cause of it is.

61
00:06:55,504 --> 00:06:59,209
And he finds himself a nice place near modern day Bodh Gaya,

62
00:07:01,466 --> 00:07:04,490
And there's a village close by where he can get some food.

63
00:07:05,072 --> 00:07:10,319
And he sits and he becomes liberated from suffering in his own terms.

64
00:07:13,903 --> 00:07:22,235
And such is his demeanor that when he turns up again to see his friends because he thinks, well, you know, who can I teach?

65
00:07:22,274 --> 00:07:25,959
And at first, you know, he has that doubt about whether it's worth doing it.

66
00:07:28,603 --> 00:07:30,867
But then when he approaches his people...

67
00:07:31,942 --> 00:07:37,110
they first of all turn off, you know, like he's gone soft.

68
00:07:38,071 --> 00:07:39,632
They don't want to know him.

69
00:07:39,653 --> 00:07:45,240
But as he comes, approaches them, they begin to see that there's something about him which has changed.

70
00:07:46,122 --> 00:07:56,415
And in the conversation that follows, which is in the Vinaya rather than in the scriptures, he's constantly asking them,

71
00:07:56,834 --> 00:07:58,697
Have you ever heard me speak like this before?

72
00:07:59,156 --> 00:08:06,288
So he's made a real profound breakthrough and he's trying to get it across to them.

73
00:08:06,307 --> 00:08:12,237
And that breakthrough goes back to that childhood way of looking at things.

74
00:08:12,257 --> 00:08:16,642
So when we're born, we've already got it, you know.

75
00:08:17,725 --> 00:08:21,389
It's there at birth, this ability to just receive.

76
00:08:22,517 --> 00:08:28,983
And it is said that during the first four months, it's just a catastrophe of information.

77
00:08:29,004 --> 00:08:32,827
You know, we're seeing things, we're hearing things, and it's just coming at us.

78
00:08:33,849 --> 00:08:36,311
And there's no objectivity.

79
00:08:36,410 --> 00:08:39,333
We're sort of absorbed in the process.

80
00:08:41,375 --> 00:08:46,061
And that little baby knows very clearly what's pleasant and unpleasant.

81
00:08:46,181 --> 00:08:48,643
So you're born directly into that duality.

82
00:08:49,855 --> 00:08:53,659
And then it would seem after four months, you begin to push the world outwards.

83
00:08:55,903 --> 00:08:59,327
And the first object tends to be your carer, you know, your mother.

84
00:09:00,809 --> 00:09:10,643
And so eventually, what was right in the head here, happening here, becomes out there, sort of pushing it out there, becomes an object outside.

85
00:09:11,663 --> 00:09:15,288
And we forget that everything we're observing and seeing is actually outside.

86
00:09:16,331 --> 00:09:18,955
being put out onto the world out there.

87
00:09:19,115 --> 00:09:23,660
What we're seeing is what the mind is creating at this present time.

88
00:09:29,827 --> 00:09:42,964
And that sense of awareness that he found, that intuitive awareness that he discovered by just relaxing within himself and observing, he picked up then from that

89
00:09:43,601 --> 00:10:09,457
experience he had watching his father doing a playing ceremony and that's probably i would have thought around about the age of seven and eight because that's i think when we become a bit more self-aware in that way for instance guilt comes into into play around about the age of seven and around about the age of seven we we drop

90
00:10:09,977 --> 00:10:15,144
the idea that what we can see or what we can imagine has to be real.

91
00:10:15,423 --> 00:10:18,347
So Father Christmas can't come down the chimney anymore.

92
00:10:25,235 --> 00:10:37,149
So this awareness that he then isolates from everything else that's in the body, all the senses, the consciousnesses that arise dependent on the senses,

93
00:10:40,960 --> 00:10:46,727
Is that whole process, that whole process of investigation is the process of liberation.

94
00:10:47,308 --> 00:10:49,150
That's what he discovered.

95
00:10:49,812 --> 00:10:51,293
That's what he's trying to tell us to do.

96
00:10:52,315 --> 00:10:58,504
And this word vipassana, which just means to see clearly, you know, to really look and see.

97
00:11:01,927 --> 00:11:04,951
And he's very clear on what it is that we're trying to investigate.

98
00:11:05,192 --> 00:11:06,134
It's not amorphous.

99
00:11:06,193 --> 00:11:08,537
It's not some funny, fuzzy idea.

100
00:11:09,073 --> 00:11:10,216
He says, have a look.

101
00:11:10,255 --> 00:11:13,240
He says, have a look at desire, this process of desire.

102
00:11:15,023 --> 00:11:18,307
And he gives us three models of a human being.

103
00:11:18,908 --> 00:11:20,090
Actually, there's another one, too.

104
00:11:20,129 --> 00:11:28,403
But the three main ones are the five khandhas, whereby he deconstructs the human being as a cross section.

105
00:11:28,962 --> 00:11:30,404
So there's your physicality.

106
00:11:31,126 --> 00:11:38,236
And then your mentality is made up of your feelings, your perceptions, all your habits.

107
00:11:38,807 --> 00:11:42,172
which are made by us through acts of will.

108
00:11:42,332 --> 00:11:43,234
That's the important thing.

109
00:11:43,533 --> 00:11:46,477
They're conditioned and conditioning.

110
00:11:46,498 --> 00:11:52,346
And consciousness, which here means a screen upon which all the information lands upon.

111
00:11:55,809 --> 00:12:00,956
And then he points out that the consciousness is dependent on the six sense bases.

112
00:12:02,658 --> 00:12:05,423
There's the five obvious ones, which is your

113
00:12:06,077 --> 00:12:09,081
five physical bases, your eye, ear, nose, etc.

114
00:12:09,682 --> 00:12:15,730
And the mind itself, which is sensing your emotions and your thoughts.

115
00:12:19,195 --> 00:12:21,918
And then the final, which again is more like a cross section.

116
00:12:22,139 --> 00:12:26,284
And then he gives us a process, which is dependent origination.

117
00:12:27,586 --> 00:12:29,708
And he starts off with that sense of ignorance.

118
00:12:31,812 --> 00:12:33,293
And this ignorance isn't culpable.

119
00:12:33,374 --> 00:12:34,195
It's not as though

120
00:12:34,951 --> 00:12:37,714
You know, that four-month-old baby should have known better.

121
00:12:38,214 --> 00:12:41,076
It's just that's what happens to us.

122
00:12:41,937 --> 00:12:43,539
You know, we come in not knowing.

123
00:12:43,679 --> 00:12:45,101
That's the word, not knowing.

124
00:12:47,264 --> 00:12:50,548
And then we manufacture some idea of ourselves.

125
00:12:53,370 --> 00:12:57,495
A sense of me, you know, which concretizes round about the age of three.

126
00:12:58,316 --> 00:13:03,321
So that you have a very little individual boy and an individual girl.

127
00:13:06,067 --> 00:13:07,070
And that's necessary.

128
00:13:07,269 --> 00:13:08,851
We have to start off with a self.

129
00:13:09,734 --> 00:13:13,679
It has to be a stable sense of self, a good sense of self.

130
00:13:13,700 --> 00:13:19,909
Often in the scriptures and especially in the Dhammapada, there's a whole section on being a good self.

131
00:13:22,133 --> 00:13:25,698
But once you've established it, once it's stabilized, then we've got to get...

132
00:13:25,719 --> 00:13:27,802
It's not that you get rid of it completely.

133
00:13:27,822 --> 00:13:32,970
It's just that you recognize that it's also creating a wrong relationship of identity.

134
00:13:34,097 --> 00:13:41,306
And that every time we come into the vipassana, we've moved our identity.

135
00:13:43,248 --> 00:13:48,254
So we have a physical identity sometimes, like when you bite your tongue and you're eating.

136
00:13:49,054 --> 00:13:54,120
Just for that one moment, you and that excruciating pain are one.

137
00:13:55,902 --> 00:13:57,384
And then you get angry with yourself.

138
00:13:58,706 --> 00:13:59,966
And then you become an emotion.

139
00:14:01,048 --> 00:14:03,530
And then you might reflect upon why it happened.

140
00:14:04,186 --> 00:14:07,211
And then you become your thought processes and so on and so forth.

141
00:14:08,032 --> 00:14:18,089
And here in the Vipassana, we've accessed some place within us, this observer, this feeler, which also has a sense of self.

142
00:14:18,789 --> 00:14:20,714
And that's the one that has to be cracked.

143
00:14:20,754 --> 00:14:26,363
That's the last sense of self that has to be undone, you might say.

144
00:14:31,067 --> 00:15:00,044
in the discourse on not self which is the third discourse that he gives according to the tradition so the first one is laying out the um sorry it's the second discourse what am i saying it's the second discourse the first one is just laying out the teaching which eventually formalizes into the four noble truths but the set and and one person listening to that one of his six companions becomes what we call a stream entra right he makes a break

145
00:15:00,885 --> 00:15:28,345
through that delusive idea of self and then they all go off seemingly they all go off to get some food and they come back and have a bit of a lunch have a rest a cup of tea and then he gives his second talk centering on this anatta not self and it begins by saying you know if i were the body i could make it different right right if if if

146
00:15:28,678 --> 00:15:33,923
If the hair on my head was mine, I'd make it grow, but it'd disappear completely.

147
00:15:34,605 --> 00:15:38,928
What to do?

148
00:15:38,948 --> 00:15:43,533
And if this body and if these emotions were mine, I'd have total control over them.

149
00:15:43,552 --> 00:15:46,294
But obviously, we don't have that sort of control.

150
00:15:48,277 --> 00:15:52,981
If the sensations in my body were under my control, I'd be able to do something.

151
00:15:53,942 --> 00:15:57,605
Now, it's not as though we don't have some control, but it's very, very...

152
00:15:57,907 --> 00:15:58,668
surface.

153
00:16:00,971 --> 00:16:05,596
Even if you think about your body, have we any idea at this moment what the spleen is doing?

154
00:16:05,736 --> 00:16:08,120
I'm not so sure I even know what a spleen is.

155
00:16:09,802 --> 00:16:13,866
All I know is you don't want to get rid of it or try not to get rid of it.

156
00:16:17,831 --> 00:16:23,038
And then he talks about impermanence and he says, you know, if it's impermanent, how can it be me?

157
00:16:23,058 --> 00:16:25,601
So he's struggling with this word atta.

158
00:16:26,121 --> 00:16:30,886
So this was the word which was being used for an eternal self.

159
00:16:31,346 --> 00:16:35,611
It's the same word atman in Sanskrit.

160
00:16:35,631 --> 00:16:39,395
So it's used by the Hindus or the Brahmins.

161
00:16:39,456 --> 00:16:41,277
It's not Hinduism as such yet.

162
00:16:41,317 --> 00:16:42,097
It's Brahmanism.

163
00:16:42,138 --> 00:16:43,219
We call it Brahmanism.

164
00:16:43,960 --> 00:16:50,626
It's used by other teachers, such as the Jain teacher.

165
00:16:51,113 --> 00:16:57,438
to point to something which is not part of this psychophysical world, right?

166
00:16:57,479 --> 00:17:00,261
Psychophysical material world.

167
00:17:01,984 --> 00:17:06,388
And the discourse is not saying we don't have a self.

168
00:17:06,409 --> 00:17:08,790
So remember, you know, it does get confusing.

169
00:17:09,652 --> 00:17:15,958
Here what the discourse is a pointer, which is saying, look, if there is this self, you know, where is it?

170
00:17:16,018 --> 00:17:16,699
What is it?

171
00:17:17,978 --> 00:17:20,280
And the next point he comes to is impermanent.

172
00:17:20,300 --> 00:17:30,232
He says, well, if this self is meant to be an eternal soul, an eternal spirit in our language, if it's so, it can't arise and pass away.

173
00:17:31,454 --> 00:17:42,709
So even by investigating everything that we're experiencing as momentary experiences, we're beginning to understand that anything I experience can't be me.

174
00:17:43,911 --> 00:17:45,031
It can't be this soul.

175
00:17:45,990 --> 00:17:48,374
Can't be this permanent sense of self.

176
00:17:49,615 --> 00:17:52,740
Even the sense of self disappears when we sleep.

177
00:17:52,980 --> 00:17:54,222
So I can't be that either.

178
00:17:55,964 --> 00:18:08,864
So it was really trying to point people to really investigate whether there was this sense of, whether there was this eternal soul.

179
00:18:10,905 --> 00:18:13,450
And it was this process of investigation

180
00:18:13,632 --> 00:18:36,518
which is the liberating factor right so this is the path you might say this the the specific path of the buddha was the process of investigation and then of course he says if something arises and passes away and you're clinging on to it then it's going to cause suffering and that's the dukkha

181
00:18:38,117 --> 00:18:45,365
In a later way of explaining that, he talks about the three types of suffering.

182
00:18:45,425 --> 00:18:49,609
So there's the suffering of reactivity, dukkha-dukkha, right?

183
00:18:50,550 --> 00:18:52,653
Life has suffering whether we like it or not.

184
00:18:53,755 --> 00:18:59,560
But how we relate to that, the unpleasantness of life, that also causes suffering.

185
00:19:00,842 --> 00:19:04,445
And everything is suffering if we're attached to something.

186
00:19:04,797 --> 00:19:08,461
And we get attached to what is pleasant, to what is beautiful.

187
00:19:10,723 --> 00:19:14,909
And that the impermanence of that, catching the impermanence that we can let go.

188
00:19:14,969 --> 00:19:16,691
We accept beauty.

189
00:19:16,830 --> 00:19:24,240
So that's the thing is it's accepting and enjoying beauty, enjoying that ecstatic mental state.

190
00:19:25,080 --> 00:19:27,462
And when it goes to remind ourselves, it's gone.

191
00:19:27,884 --> 00:19:29,244
That will never repeat itself.

192
00:19:29,285 --> 00:19:30,686
I'll get something like it.

193
00:19:31,257 --> 00:19:33,358
But I'm chasing the dragon.

194
00:19:33,459 --> 00:19:36,702
Well, it's the same psychology as any drug addict.

195
00:19:39,625 --> 00:19:41,728
And then finally, the sankhata dukkha.

196
00:19:41,807 --> 00:19:48,796
It's the dukkha, the suffering or the unsatisfaction that comes by not seeing that everything's compounded.

197
00:19:49,517 --> 00:19:55,403
There's nothing that has any solidity, that has any substance.

198
00:19:59,207 --> 00:19:59,948
And we know that.

199
00:20:00,096 --> 00:20:14,493
On a physical level from our science, you know, I mean, it's somebody once said to me, if we took all the space out of the body, we'd end up with something like a centimeter cube of matter.

200
00:20:16,875 --> 00:20:22,021
So that's what we're made of, these subatomic energies, whatever.

201
00:20:22,682 --> 00:20:24,265
It's magic when you think about it.

202
00:20:31,045 --> 00:20:40,454
So it's investigating these three characteristics that lead us to discover within ourselves something which is not part of that process.

203
00:20:42,336 --> 00:20:43,659
He doesn't like to name it.

204
00:20:45,160 --> 00:20:48,042
He doesn't like to call it something.

205
00:20:48,063 --> 00:20:52,488
He prefers to talk about the experience Nibbana.

206
00:20:55,310 --> 00:20:59,736
And what he says about Nibbana is that there's nothing in it

207
00:21:00,593 --> 00:21:04,479
which you've ever experienced or can experience.

208
00:21:04,499 --> 00:21:08,684
It is beyond the body and mind and heart.

209
00:21:08,704 --> 00:21:09,807
It's beyond all.

210
00:21:09,846 --> 00:21:15,015
Whatever we call being a human being, it's not that.

211
00:21:18,240 --> 00:21:28,255
And then in another scripture where he's in a sense pushed, we might say, by the question

212
00:21:28,605 --> 00:21:30,688
to answer in a very direct way.

213
00:21:32,170 --> 00:21:33,530
And it's called the Kevada Sutta.

214
00:21:33,550 --> 00:21:42,619
It's very famous amongst monastics, amongst certain monastics, because it goes against the idea that Nibbana is nothing.

215
00:21:42,819 --> 00:21:47,064
You know, like it's a sort of clever way of talking about annihilation.

216
00:21:48,786 --> 00:21:53,990
And there's this monk Kevada, and he wants to know where the world comes to an end.

217
00:21:54,451 --> 00:21:58,596
So now the world in this sense, and the Buddha often uses it in this sense,

218
00:21:58,828 --> 00:22:01,112
is the world you're experiencing.

219
00:22:01,271 --> 00:22:02,934
It's your world, right?

220
00:22:03,715 --> 00:22:05,699
It's not the world as an objective thing.

221
00:22:08,281 --> 00:22:21,901
And he goes and asks somebody, and they don't know, and he asks these Devas, these gods, and they keep saying, well, you know, we don't really know the answer to that.

222
00:22:22,582 --> 00:22:24,845
You need to go up higher to the next load of gods.

223
00:22:25,365 --> 00:22:26,186
And he goes...

224
00:22:26,622 --> 00:22:35,311
He goes up and up through all these scales of godly realms, deva realms, till he gets to the great Brahma, who is the creator.

225
00:22:35,952 --> 00:22:41,199
And he says to Brahma, you know, where does the world come to an end?

226
00:22:41,900 --> 00:22:44,742
And Brahma answers, I am Brahma.

227
00:22:44,762 --> 00:22:46,065
I am the creator of the world.

228
00:22:46,505 --> 00:22:49,188
I am the all-powerful, the all-knower, and so on and so forth.

229
00:22:49,228 --> 00:22:51,330
And he says, I didn't ask you that.

230
00:22:51,351 --> 00:22:52,511
I wanted to know.

231
00:22:53,420 --> 00:22:54,681
where the world comes to an end.

232
00:22:54,721 --> 00:22:55,842
And this happens three times.

233
00:22:55,903 --> 00:22:59,105
It's quite a funny discourse.

234
00:22:59,125 --> 00:23:02,950
And then Abram pulls him aside, you see, sort of behind a curtain.

235
00:23:03,170 --> 00:23:08,654
And he says, listen, he said, I don't want them to know that I don't know the answer to that question.

236
00:23:09,276 --> 00:23:10,457
But I do know who knows.

237
00:23:10,738 --> 00:23:11,458
And that's the Buddha.

238
00:23:11,798 --> 00:23:13,380
And you made a mistake coming up here.

239
00:23:13,420 --> 00:23:14,280
You should have gone to him.

240
00:23:15,561 --> 00:23:18,144
So he nips down back to see the Buddha.

241
00:23:18,782 --> 00:23:21,306
And he asks the Buddha, where does the world come to an end?

242
00:23:21,326 --> 00:23:23,429
And he says, that's not the right question.

243
00:23:23,910 --> 00:23:27,714
The question is, where does the world not find a footing?

244
00:23:28,855 --> 00:23:35,223
So Nibbana exists at the same time as the world, as it was for him, the Buddha.

245
00:23:37,166 --> 00:23:38,628
And then he comes out with a statement.

246
00:23:38,648 --> 00:23:40,290
He says, there is a consciousness.

247
00:23:41,592 --> 00:23:47,440
So now, you see, it's like whenever somebody has

248
00:23:47,673 --> 00:24:05,078
an insight into the human nature or into the world as it is, there's always a struggle for a word because the words that we have are always based on history, are always based on what we know.

249
00:24:05,098 --> 00:24:14,492
So, for instance, Freud, you know, he has a real deep insight into the human psyche and there's no words that he can use, so he makes them up.

250
00:24:14,573 --> 00:24:17,477
The id, the ego, the superego.

251
00:24:18,519 --> 00:24:21,544
So the Buddha doesn't particularly make up a new word.

252
00:24:22,305 --> 00:24:25,909
He is using consciousness in a particular way.

253
00:24:28,412 --> 00:24:35,621
And what he says is that there is this consciousness which is non-manifestive.

254
00:24:35,681 --> 00:24:41,929
And what he means by that is you won't find anything that the six senses

255
00:24:42,567 --> 00:24:43,188
offer us.

256
00:24:43,768 --> 00:24:50,734
So that's one way of looking at a human being, that the consciousness is based upon one of the six senses.

257
00:24:50,755 --> 00:24:54,699
You're either seeing or hearing, feeling, thinking.

258
00:24:55,901 --> 00:25:01,165
And he says there's nothing, there's no manifestation within that consciousness.

259
00:25:02,968 --> 00:25:06,971
And then he says that there's no boundary.

260
00:25:09,212 --> 00:25:10,075
There's no boundary.

261
00:25:10,414 --> 00:25:16,788
In other words, there's nothing there which there is a relationship to.

262
00:25:17,689 --> 00:25:21,115
It's complete, whole and entire unto itself.

263
00:25:23,780 --> 00:25:25,183
And then he says it's full of light.

264
00:25:27,648 --> 00:25:31,997
And that's one experience, an experience of nibbana.

265
00:25:35,133 --> 00:25:38,297
So, that's our aim.

266
00:25:38,457 --> 00:25:43,104
Nibbāna can be experienced in different ways, right?

267
00:25:43,183 --> 00:25:49,972
I mean, that is a specific experience of the Buddha within, in itself.

268
00:25:51,273 --> 00:26:03,029
But every time we sit in the position of the observer, we're right, we're actually almost on the point of a Nibbāna experience.

269
00:26:04,292 --> 00:26:09,598
Because when you're in that position, ask yourself, am I suffering?

270
00:26:13,242 --> 00:26:17,588
It might be that there is some very negative mental state there.

271
00:26:19,510 --> 00:26:24,416
You might be feeling very sad about somebody, somebody who's died, for instance, a friend.

272
00:26:25,998 --> 00:26:29,962
And as soon as you become aware of it, as soon as it's there,

273
00:26:30,719 --> 00:26:34,803
You're allowing the heart to express its sadness and therefore its healing.

274
00:26:35,983 --> 00:26:40,429
But whatever is aware of it, ask yourself, is that actually suffering?

275
00:26:41,450 --> 00:26:44,933
So this is a magical position to find within ourselves.

276
00:26:47,635 --> 00:26:50,499
It doesn't heal the heart, it allows the heart to heal itself.

277
00:26:53,762 --> 00:26:55,064
That's all the heart wants to do.

278
00:26:55,503 --> 00:26:58,988
The heart just wants to express its problems.

279
00:26:59,592 --> 00:27:04,758
And it expresses it in feelings.

280
00:27:04,778 --> 00:27:08,021
And that's where we start dealing with these so-called hindrances.

281
00:27:12,125 --> 00:27:17,311
All those things that are agitating, are depressing.

282
00:27:19,494 --> 00:27:29,346
You know, the five, all the ones to do with desires that we want, all the aversions that we have, which include the fears and anxieties.

283
00:27:30,018 --> 00:27:56,650
all the internal all that dullness and lethargy which is has been a way of indulgence and a way of suppressing stuff you know like often when we when we're not in a in a miserable state like we'll just just throw ourselves on the sofa and fall asleep and so it's a nice way of just pushing things away pushing things away and of course it's very pleasant isn't it you know

284
00:27:57,051 --> 00:28:11,913
I mean, you wake up in the morning on a Sunday and you might just have been tempted just to keep sleeping, you know, on that subliminal state, you know, where you just keep turning over and you might get up and have a cup of tea and get back in the bed.

285
00:28:13,615 --> 00:28:16,039
So there's all this sort of that laziness.

286
00:28:16,140 --> 00:28:18,743
Well, of course, it's building up a mental state.

287
00:28:19,223 --> 00:28:24,392
And that's what we often feel when we're sitting, right, as a person.

288
00:28:25,047 --> 00:28:26,087
as a hindrance.

289
00:28:26,107 --> 00:28:31,314
A hindrance meaning it's the danger of us being pulled into it, of giving into it.

290
00:28:31,834 --> 00:28:37,180
That's why it's a hindrance, is that they're actually teaching us something, these hindrances.

291
00:28:38,621 --> 00:28:52,236
And then there's all that area of shame and guilt, remorse, sort of secondary stuff that comes when we've not behaved in a way that's moral or ethical.

292
00:28:58,307 --> 00:29:01,791
And there's also included in that the sense of just that restlessness.

293
00:29:03,354 --> 00:29:05,396
A restlessness which can be physical.

294
00:29:06,017 --> 00:29:07,138
It can be emotional.

295
00:29:07,479 --> 00:29:08,240
It can be mental.

296
00:29:08,780 --> 00:29:09,801
It can be the three of them.

297
00:29:10,363 --> 00:29:11,824
And you just can't stop fidgeting.

298
00:29:11,844 --> 00:29:16,309
You can't stop doing something, you know.

299
00:29:16,329 --> 00:29:18,152
And the final one is doubt.

300
00:29:18,271 --> 00:29:19,614
But this is a type of doubt.

301
00:29:19,634 --> 00:29:24,720
I mean, the Buddha definitely wants us to doubt in the sense of ask ourselves questions.

302
00:29:25,577 --> 00:29:30,224
you know, is what the Buddha's teaching true for us.

303
00:29:30,305 --> 00:29:32,307
Remember, this is a process of investigation.

304
00:29:32,667 --> 00:29:34,951
So belief becomes a real hindrance.

305
00:29:35,833 --> 00:29:39,337
He doesn't want us to believe anything, but he does want us to have confidence.

306
00:29:40,720 --> 00:29:43,644
And that's what skeptical doubt takes away from us.

307
00:29:44,665 --> 00:29:52,917
Because if you don't have confidence, if you don't have, then that doubt takes you over in anything, in any walk of life, you know, and you can't move.

308
00:29:53,624 --> 00:29:54,965
you're paralyzed.

309
00:29:55,086 --> 00:30:07,304
I once had a student, I don't know what happened to him, but he couldn't even, he got into this terrible psychological place of extreme doubt.

310
00:30:07,364 --> 00:30:09,246
He couldn't decide whether to get out of bed or not.

311
00:30:10,248 --> 00:30:12,310
I mean, it's just amazing when you think about it.

312
00:30:13,071 --> 00:30:14,733
And I'm not so sure I could help.

313
00:30:14,753 --> 00:30:23,547
I'm not sure I helped him except to say, you know, make a decision at some point to get out of bed and get out of bed.

314
00:30:25,113 --> 00:30:27,635
But he couldn't motivate himself.

315
00:30:27,855 --> 00:30:29,498
It was very, very strange.

316
00:30:30,219 --> 00:30:34,484
Unfortunately, I lost contact, but I presume he's found a way out of that, you know.

317
00:30:37,749 --> 00:30:53,989
So these mental states, these hindrances that come up are actually to be used in order to keep reinforcing in ourselves to reestablish a different relationship with the world, you know, not me, not mine.

318
00:30:56,685 --> 00:31:18,221
and of course the danger is then that you you're opting out you're finding a place where you're becoming um non-engaged and that's why whenever we practice vipassana it's always good to do a bit of meta you know because that re-engages us and uh and basically that's what uh

319
00:31:18,724 --> 00:31:23,813
the Buddha did, if you remember having attained this full liberation.

320
00:31:24,093 --> 00:31:29,320
No, just before that, you get the great doubt where Mara attacks him, you see.

321
00:31:29,480 --> 00:31:38,755
So he's sitting there and all those old desires are coming up, you know, to go back to the family, back to the life that he once loved, et cetera, et cetera.

322
00:31:39,757 --> 00:31:45,204
And he tries to steady that doubt by touching the earth, right?

323
00:31:46,518 --> 00:31:58,131
And the earth goddess rises and says, you've got every right to seek this liberation because Mara is telling him that he's not good enough.

324
00:31:58,191 --> 00:31:58,770
He's no good.

325
00:31:59,051 --> 00:32:00,212
It's a waste of time.

326
00:32:00,292 --> 00:32:05,198
Why are you doing this?

327
00:32:05,218 --> 00:32:14,127
And having perfected the virtue of generosity, it means that his purpose wasn't just for himself.

328
00:32:14,664 --> 00:32:20,472
It was actually to try and recognise that if he found it, he could help everybody else.

329
00:32:23,676 --> 00:32:24,999
And that was his engagement.

330
00:32:25,138 --> 00:32:28,784
That was what gave him that courage to just break through.

331
00:32:28,824 --> 00:32:38,916
And then afterwards, having overcome the doubt that anyone would actually understand him, sends him into 40 years, isn't it?

332
00:32:39,017 --> 00:32:42,461
45 years of teaching.

333
00:32:43,807 --> 00:32:45,790
And that's what he devotes his life to.

334
00:32:47,272 --> 00:33:01,255
So just to sum up, right awareness, you know, bring to mind that childlike way of looking at things before conceptual thinking, before words, just to be able to see.

335
00:33:02,355 --> 00:33:05,381
And we can practice that just a very simple way.

336
00:33:05,520 --> 00:33:07,002
You know, we can stare at something.

337
00:33:08,345 --> 00:33:11,690
Just stare at it and let the information come to us.

338
00:33:12,652 --> 00:33:12,751
Yeah.

339
00:33:15,179 --> 00:33:28,335
And what it is, we're actually investigating these three characteristics and to use the five hindrances as ways of seeing these three characteristics.

340
00:33:29,517 --> 00:33:37,507
And slowly but surely, you know, I'm sure you've all experienced life getting a little bit better because of our practice.

341
00:33:37,527 --> 00:33:39,009
Just a little.

342
00:33:39,028 --> 00:33:41,131
So abandon progress, right?

343
00:33:41,171 --> 00:33:42,292
That's a poison, honestly.

344
00:33:42,313 --> 00:33:42,894
It's a poison.

345
00:33:43,473 --> 00:33:44,055
Always get...

346
00:33:44,727 --> 00:33:48,431
You know, students saying, I'm not progressing or where am I going?

347
00:33:48,810 --> 00:33:49,991
You're not going anywhere.

348
00:33:50,011 --> 00:33:52,934
You're standing right here and you're observing process.

349
00:33:53,476 --> 00:33:59,902
And in observing process, that is the process of liberation.

350
00:33:59,922 --> 00:34:04,666
To see and understand how things have come to arise.

351
00:34:04,686 --> 00:34:06,189
That's the Buddhist sentence.

352
00:34:07,730 --> 00:34:10,632
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

353
00:34:11,052 --> 00:34:19,358
And that by your devotion to practice, you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

